<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Characteristic Species</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Chrysolepis</i> <i>sempervirens</i> is dominant in the shrub canopy with <i>Amelanchier</i> <i>alnifolia</i>, <i>Arctostaphylos</i> <i>nevadensis</i>, <i>Arctostaphylos</i> <i>patula</i>, <i>Ceanothus</i> <i>cordulatus</i>, <i>Ceanothus</i> <i>velutinus</i>, <i>Garrya</i> <i>fremontii</i>, <i>Holodiscus</i> <i>discolor</i>, <i>Prunus</i> <i>emarginata</i>, <i>Quercus</i> <i>sadleriana</i>, <i>Quercus</i> <i>vacciniifolia</i> and <i>Symphoricarpos</i> <i>mollis</i>. Emergent conifer trees may be present at low cover. </div>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Vegetation Layers</h4>
	<div class="text">  Shrubs < 3 m; canopy is intermittent to continuous. Herbaceous layer is sparse. </div>
</div>

        
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Membership Rules</h4>
	<ul class="text">
		
		<li><i>Chrysolepis sempervirens</i> > 50% relative cover (Keeler-Wolf et al. 2003b).</li>
		
	</ul>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Habitats</h4>
	<div class="text"> Ridges and steep upper slopes. Soils are shallow, commonly granitic, and rocky.  </div>
</div>

        
