<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Chrysolepis sempervirens </i>is an evergreen spreading shrub that grows to 2.5 m in height. This oak relative masts, producing seed crops periodically. Birds and rodents disperse the nuts, and seed predation is high. Cached seeds are viable for five years under cold, dry conditions. Shrubs may both facilitate seedling establishment of conifers and suppress their growth (Howard 1992d). <br/>
<br/>
<i>Chrysolepis sempervirens </i>can dominate stands of montane chaparral or form an understory layer in coniferous forests. Stands are most extensive in the subalpine belt. Self-perpetuating stands exist on shallow soils; transitional stands to <i>Abies concolor </i>and <i>A. magnifica </i>forests occupy deeper soils more commonly in the montane belt. Stands are regularly adjacent to or embedded within stands of the <i>Quercus vacciniifolia </i>alliance from the central Sierra Nevada to the Klamath Mountains. Stands tend to become more common relative to those of <i>Quercus vacciniifolia </i>in the central and southern Sierra Nevada. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
