    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Klamath Mountains</b> (M261Ae, Ag, Aj, An, Aq-t). Stands are local and infrequent at subalpine elevations; <i>Quercus vacciniifolia</i> stands are more common in this section. Montane stands include <i>Ceanothus velutinus</i> and <i>Q. sadleriana. Chrysolepis sempervirens</i> is a common understory plant in open, pine-dominated stands in the eastern portions of the section at montane elevations.</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast Ranges</b> (M261Ba). Occasional small stands occur in the higher elevations in the section. Stands on South Fork Mountain are transitional to those of <i>Chrysolepis chrysophylla</i> and are surrounded by young, post-fire <i>Abies concolor</i> forest stands.</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada</b> (M261Ea-b, Ed, Eh, Em, Eo-r, Eu). Stands occur at upper elevations (montane to subalpine) throughout the section. Stands at Church Dome and Moses Mountain RNAs (Cheng 2004), in Sierra Co. (Conard and Radosevich 1982), on the eastern slope of the Sierra Nevada (Mozingo 1987), throughout much of Kings Canyon and Sequoia national parks (S. Haultain, pers. comm. 2003), and in Yosemite National Park (Keeler-Wolf et al. 2003b) are characteristic of the alliance. Stands of the alliance replace those of the <i>Quercus vacciniifolia</i> alliance south of Yosemite National Park; they are particularly common on the Kern Plateau. Isolated stands adjacent to <i>Pinus albicaulis, P. monticola,</i> and <i>P. contorta</i> ssp. <i>murrayana</i> forests occur above 3000 m east of the crest.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Mountains and Valleys</b> (M262Bb, Bd-e, Bh, Bm). Occasional stands occur in the high Transverse Range and near Mount San Jacinto. These stands associate with <i>Abies concolor, P. contorta</i> ssp. <i>murrayana, P. flexilis,</i> and<i> P. jeffreyi</i> forests.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern Cascades</b> (M261Dd, Df-j). Stands in the Medicine Lake Highlands area and at the Shasta Mudflow and Mud Lake RNAs (Cheng 2004) have emergent conifers. They exist adjacent to stands of the <i>Artemisia tridentata</i> and <i>Ceanothus velutinus</i> alliances.</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Many stands in the northern half of the state are transitory to coniferous forest. Stands in the southern half tend to be subalpine and are generally not subject to the effects of timber harvest. Stands on the edge of the Great Basin may show relatively short-term effects of climate change. </div>
</div>

    

    

